                <ab> 
                    <lb n="1"/><w lemma="ζάω">ζῇς</w>
                </ab>
            </div>
            <div type="textpart" subtype="section" n="Below the tabula" >
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><w lemma="ζάω">ζῇς</w>
                </ab>
            </div>
            <div type="textpart" subtype="section" n="Below the tabula" >
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><w lemma="ψύχω">ἔψυγμαι</w>
                </ab>
            </div>
            </div>
            <div type="apparatus">
                <ab>This comes from ψύχω. Cf. T15.2 and T29.5. “I have been chilled!” Is the reference to the cooling shade of the basement level? The case of T29.5, however, where it is written on a testicle, suggests that a sexual meaning (or double-entendre?) may be intended, whether that refers to the cooling of emotion or more specifically to the loss of an erection. There appears to be one stroke after the word, whether connected with it cannot be determined.</ab>
            </div> 
            <div type="translation">
            <div type="translation" subtype="section" n="Inside the tabula ansata">
                <ab>“May you live!”</ab>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" subtype="section" n="Inside a partly-preserved ansata">
                <ab>“May you live!”</ab>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" subtype="section" n="Below the second graffito">
                <ab>“I have been chilled!”</ab>
            </div>
